Aim:

Simulation of Quality Control System

Theory:

A quality control system is used in industries to inspect products and ensure they meet required
standards before delivery or sale. Products arriving for inspection are checked by available inspectors 
or workers. If all inspectors are busy, products wait in a queue until service becomes available.

This simulation models a multiple-server quality control system with a single queue.

The system mainly consists of:

Product arrival rate
Inspection/service time
Queue length
Waiting time
Number of inspectors/workers
COMMANDS:
GENERATE
Creates products arriving for inspection.
QUEUE
Places products into the waiting line.
ENTER
Allocates one available worker/server.
DEPART
Removes products from the queue once inspection starts.
ADVANCE
Simulates inspection time.
LEAVE
Releases the worker after inspection.
TERMINATE
Removes the product from the system or stops simulation.
STORAGE
Defines multiple identical workers/servers.
Scenario Overview:

The quality control system contains:

Three inspectors/workers
One common inspection queue
Continuous product arrivals

Products arrive randomly for inspection. If all inspectors are busy, products wait in the queue 
until one worker becomes available.

This behaves like an M/M/C queueing system, where:

M = random arrivals
M = random inspection times
C = multiple servers
Key Components:
1. Products

Products arrive for inspection and wait if inspectors are busy.

2. Workers/Inspectors

Three inspectors perform quality checks simultaneously.

3. Queue

A single waiting line stores products waiting for inspection.

4. Inspection Process

Products undergo quality checking before leaving the system.

